yle=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''55.00%''' ''418''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|11.05% ''84''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n===Public officials===\n*'''Chicot County''': Ronald Nichols (Sheriff), Mack Ball Jr. (County Judge) Skylar King (Coroner)\n*'''Dermott''': Eric Evans (Police Chief),  (Fire Chief)\n*'''Eudora''': William El-Amin (Police Chief), Robert Bunn  (Fire Chief), Travis Collins  (Mayor)\n*'''Lake Village''': Percy Wilburn (Police Chief), Sam E. Angel II (Fire Chief), Reginald Dixon (Constable), Jo Dan Yee  (Mayor)\n*'''Ross Van Ness''': Jonathan Bradford (Fire Chief)\n*'''LakePort''': C. W. Jordan (Fire Chief)\n\n==Communities==\n\n===Cities===\n* [[Dermott, Arkansas|Dermott]]\n* [[Eudora, Arkansas|Eudora]]\n* [[Lake Village, Arkansas|Lake Village]] (county seat)\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Arkla, Arkansas|Arkla]]\n*[[Bellaire, Arkansas|Bellaire]]\n*[[Cosgrove, Arkansas|Cosgrove]]\n*[[Chicot Junction, Arkansas|Chicot Junction]]\n*[[Empire, Arkansas|Empire]]\n*[[Farmwood, Arkansas|Farmwood]]\n*[[Indian, Arkansas|Indian]]\n*[[Grand Lake, Arkansas|Grand Lake]]\n*[[Hudspeth, Arkansas|Hudspeth]]\n*[[Jennie, Arkansas|Jennie]]\n*[[Lakeport, Arkansas|Lakeport]]\n*[[Lakehall, Arkansas|Lakehall]]\n*[[McMillian Corner, Arkansas|McMillian Corner]]\n*[[Readland, Arkansas|Readland]]\n*[[Ross Van Ness, Arkansas|Ross Van Ness]]\n*[[Shives, Arkansas|Shives]]\n*[[Stuart Island, Arkansas|Stuart Island]]\n*[[Wellford, Arkansas|Wellford]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Ghost town===\n* [[Eunice, Arkansas|Eunice]]\n\n===Townships===\n[[File:Chicot County Arkansas 2010 Township Map large.jpg|thumb|Townships in Chicot County, Arkansas as of 2010]]\n\n{{Arkansas Townships About|County = Chicot}}\n<ref>{{Cite map\n | publisher = U. S. Census Bureau\n | title = 2011 Boundary and Annexation Survey (BAS): Chicot County, AR\n | url = http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/cou/c05017_chicot/BAS11C20501700000_000.pdf\n | accessdate = 2011-08-11\n | url-status = dead\n | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121019144520/http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/cou/c05017_chicot/BAS11C20501700000_000.pdf\n | archivedate = 2012-10-19\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/maps/block/2010/cousub/dc10blk_st05_cousub.html#C | title = Arkansas: 2010 Census Block Maps - County Subdivision | publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]] | accessdate = May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\n* Bowie ([[Dermott, Arkansas|Dermott]])\n* Carlton ([[Lake Village, Arkansas|Lake Village]])\n* Planters ([[Eudora, Arkansas|Eudora]])\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Larry D. Alexander]]- Visual artist, writer, Bible teacher<ref>[http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=7313 - Encyclopedia of Arkansas - Larry Dell Alexander - 1953-]</ref>\n*[[Jim Cain (defensive end)|Jim Cain]] - American player of [[gridiron football]]\n*[[Robert Lee Hill|Robert L. Hill]] - founder of the [[Progressive Farmers and Household Union of America]]\n*[[Mark McElroy (Arkansas politician)|Mark D. McElroy]] - State representative for Chicot County since 2013; resides in [[Desha County, Arkansas|Desha County]]\n*[[Lycurgus Johnson]], the owner of the Lakeport Plantation, later a state congressman.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\">Thomas A. DeBlack, [http://www.encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=1681 Lycurgus Leonidas Johnson (1818\u20131876)], ''The Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture'', March 23, 2007</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of lakes in Chicot County, Arkansas]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Chicot County, Arkansas]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Geographic Location\n| Centre    = Chicot County, Arkansas\n| North     = [[Desha County, Arkansas|Desha County]]\n| Northeast = [[Bolivar County, Mississippi]]\n| East      = [[Washington County, Mississippi]]\n| Southeast = [[Issaquena County, Mississippi]]\n| South     = [[East Carroll Parish, Louisiana]]\n| Southwest = [[West Carroll Parish, Louisiana]]\n| West      = [[Ashley County, Arkansas|Ashley County]]\n| Northwest = [[Drew County, Arkansas|Drew County]]\n}}\n\n{{Chicot County, Arkansas}}\n{{Arkansas}}\n\n{{coord|33|17|53|N|91|16|30|W|region:US-AR_type:adm2nd_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chicot County, Arkansas| ]]\n[[Category:1823 establishments in Arkansas Territory]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1823]]\n[[Category:Arkansas counties on the Mississippi River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Chicot County\n| state = Arkansas\n| seal = \n| founded year = 1823\n| founded date = October 25\n| seat wl = Lake Village\n| largest city wl = Dermott\n| area_total_sq_mi = 691\n| area_land_sq_mi = 644\n| area_water_sq_mi = 47\n| area percentage = 6.7%\n| population_as_of = 2010\n| population_total = 11800\n| pop_est_as_of = 2018\n| population_est = 10438\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| web = http://chicotcounty.arkansas.gov/index\n| ex image = Chicot County Courthouse 001.jpg\n| ex image cap = [[Chicot County Courthouse]] in Lake Village\n| district = 1st\n| time zone = Central\n| leader type = Sheriff \n| leader name = Ronald Nichols\n}}\n\n'''Chicot County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the southeastern corner of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Arkansas]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 11,800.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/05/05017.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> The [[county seat]] is [[Lake Village, Arkansas|Lake Village]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509170006/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2015-05-09 }}</ref> Chicot County is Arkansas's 10th county, formed on October 25, 1823, and named after Point Chicot on the [[Mississippi River]]. It is part of the [[Arkansas Delta]], lowlands along the river that have been historically important as an area for large-scale cotton cultivation.\n\nLandmarks around the county include [[Lake Chicot]], North America's largest [[oxbow lake]] and Arkansas's largest natural lake; the site of [[Charles Lindbergh]]'s first night-time flight; and the legendary burial site of [[Hernando de Soto (explorer)|Hernando De Soto]], near Lake Village.\n\n==History==\nSpanish explorer Hernando de Soto came to this area with his expedition in 1542, settling for a time in the village or territory known as ''[[Guachoya]]''. The European-American town of Lake Village later developed in the 19th century at Lake Chicot, formed by an oxbow of the Mississippi River. Eighteenth-century French colonists named it ''Chicot'' because of the many cypress trees in the waterways. The word is translated to \"stumpy, or knobby\".\n\nThe area along the Mississippi River and major tributaries was developed as cotton plantations, the major commodity crop before and after the [[American Civil War]] of 1861-1865. Enslaved African Americans formed the labor force, comprising a majority of the population in the antebellum years. Major [[Plantations in the American South|large cotton plantations]] included [[Sunnyside Plantation|Sunnyside]] (owned in the 20th century by [[LeRoy Percy]], planter and US Senator from [[Greenville, Mississippi]]); Florence, Patria, Pastoria, Luna, and [[Lakeport Plantation|Lakeport]].<ref name=\"gatewood\">{{cite journal |last=Gatewood |first=Willard B, Jr. |title=Sunnyside: The Evolution of an Arkansas Plantation, 1840-1945 |journal=The Arkansas Historical Quarterly |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=5\u201329 |jstor=40022326 | date = Spring 1991   }}</ref>\n\nDuring the war, Union and Confederate forces fought at the [[Battle of Old River Lake]] from June 5 to June 6, 1864.\n\nThe population of the rural county has declined since its peak in 1940. Earlier in the century, boll weevils threatened the cotton crop, and many African Americans left in the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] for opportunity in northern and midwestern industrial cities. In addition, mechanization of agriculture and consolidation into industrial-style farms has reduced the need for farm labor.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|691|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|644|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|47|sqmi}} (6.7%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/counties_list_05.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 25, 2015|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files}}</ref>\n\n===Major highways===\n{{div col}}\n*[[Image:US 65.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Highway 65]]\n*[[Image:US 82.svg|20px]] [[U.S. Highway 82]]\n*[[Image:US 165.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Highway 165]]\n*[[Image:US 278.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Highway 278]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 8.svg|20px]] [[Arkansas Highway 8|Highway 8]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 35.svg|20px]] [[Arkansas Highway 35|Highway 35]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 159.svg|25px]] [[Arkansas Highway 159|Highway 159]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 52.svg|25px]] [[Arkansas Highway 52|Highway 52]]\n{{div col end}}\nArkansas 144\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Desha County, Arkansas|Desha County]] (north)\n* [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]], [[Mississippi]] (northeast)\n* [[Washington County, Mississippi|Washington County]], [[Mississippi]] (east)\n* [[Issaquena County, Mississippi|Issaquena County]], [[Mississippi]] (southeast)\n* [[East Carroll Parish, Louisiana|East Carroll Parish]], [[Louisiana]] (south)\n* [[West Carroll Parish, Louisiana|West Carroll Parish]], [[Louisiana]] (south)\n* [[Morehouse Parish, Louisiana|Morehouse Parish]], [[Louisiana]] (southwest)\n* [[Ashley County, Arkansas|Ashley County]] (west)\n* [[Drew County, Arkansas|Drew County]] (northwest)\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 1165\n|1840= 3806\n|1850= 5115\n|1860= 9234\n|1870= 7214\n|1880= 10117\n|1890= 11419\n|1900= 14528\n|1910= 21987\n|1920= 21749\n|1930= 22646\n|1940= 27452\n|1950= 22306\n|1960= 18990\n|1970= 18164\n|1980= 17793\n|1990= 15713\n|2000= 14117\n|2010= 11800\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=10438\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790\u20131960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> 1900\u20131990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/ar190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|editor-last=Forstall|editor-first=Richard L.|date=March 27, 1995|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref><br />1990\u20132000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|date=April 2, 2001|accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> 2010\u20132016<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\n[[Image:USA Chicot County, Arkansas age pyramid.svg|thumb|left|150px|Age pyramid Chicot County<ref>Based on [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]] data</ref>]]\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], there were 11,800 people living in the county. 54.1% were [[African American|Black or African American]], 41.2% [[White American|White]], 0.5% [[Asian American|Asian]], 0.2% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], 3.2% of some other race and 0.8 [[Multiracial American|of two or more races]]. 4.6% were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race).\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]],<ref name=\"GR8\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2011-05-14 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref> there were 14,117 people, 5,205 households, and 3,643 families living in the county.  The [[population density]] was 22 people per square mile (8/km\u00b2).  There were 5,974 housing units at an average density of 9 per square&nbsp;mile (4/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the county was 53.96% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 43.24% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.13% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.40% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 1.41% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.85% from two or more races.  2.88% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 5,205 households out of which 31.70% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 43.70% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 22.00% had a female householder with no husband present, and 30.00% were non-families. 26.90% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.00% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.58 and the average family size was 3.12.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 27.50% under the age of 18, 8.60% from 18 to 24, 26.40% from 25 to 44, 22.20% from 45 to 64, and 15.40% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females there were 94.20 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.90 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $22,024, and the median income for a family was $27,960. Males had a median income of $25,899 versus $17,115 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $12,825.  About 23.10% of families and 28.60% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 38.30% of those under age 18 and 20.70% of those age 65 or over.\n\nAs of 2010 the county population was 11,800.  The racial make-up was 40.35% Non-Hispanic whites, 54.08% blacks, 0.19% Native Americans, 0.47% Asians, 0.03% Pacific Islanders and 4.59% Hispanics or Latinos.\n\nSince 1940, the population of the county has collapsed. Press reports indicate that in 2013, the largest settlement in the county, [[Lake Village, Arkansas]] had two bank branches, two pharmacies, some law firms, two dollar stores, a grocery store, and no retail shops.<ref>Scratching a Living, The Economist, 8 June 2013</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nThe county voters have traditionally supported the Democratic Party. In the 20th century, the only Democratic presidential candidate to lose the county was [[George McGovern]] in 1972.<ref>[http://geoelections.free.fr/USA/elec_comtes/1972.htm Geographie Electorale]</ref> From the turn of the century until the mid-1960s and passage of federal [[civil rights]] legislation, the Democratic Party in Arkansas was largely made up of conservative whites, as blacks had been essentially [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disfranchised]] in Arkansas. Given national Democratic support for the civil rights struggle and the [[Voting Rights Act]] and other legislation, especially by President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], many blacks have supported the party and its candidates since regaining the power to exercise the franchise.\n\nWhite voters in the county have trended toward the Republican presidential candidates since the 1980s, but none has received more than 42 percent of the vote in any of the last five Presidential elections.<ref>[http://elections.nytimes.com/2008/results/president/map.html?scp=1&sq=%22election%20map&st=cse \"Electoral map (Zoom in on Arkansas)\"], ''The New York Times''</ref>\n\nThe county is part of [[Arkansas's 1st congressional district]]. In the [[Arkansas Senate]], the county is in District 26 and is represented by Democrat Eddie Cheatham. In the [[Arkansas House of Representatives]], it is in District 1 and represented by Democrat Mark McElroy. The county supported a measure prohibiting \"co-habiting couples\" from adopting.<ref>[http://www.arelections.org/index.php?ac:show:contest_countywide=1&elecid=181&countyid=9 Arkansas election site]</ref>\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin:1em 0 1em 1em; font-size:95%;\"\n\n|+ '''Chicot County vote<br /> by party in presidential elections<ref name=\"DL\">{{cite web|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>'''\n|-\n! Year\n![[Republican Party (United States)|GOP]]\n![[Democratic Party (United States)|Dem]]\n!Others\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Arkansas, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|41.09% ''1,716''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''56.27%''' ''2,350''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.64% ''110''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Par