n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randolphe_Gohi"}
{"title_page": "Charles Trotter", "text_new": "{{short description|British sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Charles Trotter\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = Charles Maitland Yorke Trotter\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1923|2|8}}\n| birth_place    = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2003|9|8|1923|2|8}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=Winter 2003 |date=Winter 2003 |volume=LXXXII  |issue=3 |page=82 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2003winter.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n| death_place    = [[Surrey]], England\n| occupation         = {{hlist|{{nowrap|Sports shooter}}|photographer}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Joan Peary|1963}}\n| partner            = \n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n* James 'Maitland' Trotter (father)\n* Margaret Trotter (mother)\n}}\n| module        =\n{{Infobox military person \n| embed         = yes\n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n|branch_label       = Branch\n| branch        = [[British Army]]\n|serviceyears_label = Service&nbsp;years\n|serviceyears   = 1940\u20131965\n| rank          = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| unit          = [[Royal Engineers]]\n| battles_label      = Conflict\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n}}\n| module2           = \n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| embed           = yes\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| country        = [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] {{small|(1951&ndash;1962)}}<br>Scotland {{small|(1958&ndash;2000)}}<br>[[Guernsey]] {{small|(1966&ndash;2001)}}\n| sport          = [[Sport shooter|Rifle shooting]]\n| club           = Guernsey Rifle Club\n| show-medals    = no\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Sport | [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{GGY}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Commonwealth Games}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1982 Commonwealth Games|1982 Brisbane]]|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Rifle|Fullbore singles]]}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Charles Maitland Yorke Trotter''' (8 February 1923 &ndash; 8 September 2003)<ref name=\"NRA obituary\">{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=National Rifle Association Journal |date=Spring 2004 |volume=LXXXIII |issue=1 |page=54 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2004spring.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> was a British [[Shooting sport|sports shooter]] who represented [[Guernsey]] and [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] in both fullbore and smallbore disciplines, and also sustained a successful career as a commercial photographer. Trotter's achievements in target rifle shooting make him one Guernsey's most decorated sportsmen. Best remembered for his prowess in fullbore rifle shooting, Trotter won [[National Rifle Association of the United Kingdom|H.M. The Queen's Prize]] in 1975, and is a [[Commonwealth Games]] medallist, winning a bronze medal in [[1982 Commonwealth Games|1982]] while representing Guernsey. Also a champion smallbore shooter, Trotter represented Kenya in two [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic Games]].\n\nBorn in [[Edinburgh]], Trotter was educated at [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey]], where he captained the school shooting team. He later served during [[World War II]] with the [[Royal Engineers]] before commanding a group of German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]] in [[Egypt]] after the war. After studying photography, Trotter established a photographic business in [[Nairobi]] from 1951 to 1962. He achieved considerable success as a commercial photographer, and his work is now regarded as a rich resource for the study of Kenya immediately prior to [[History of Kenya#Independence|its independence in 1962]]. During this time, Trotter represented Kenya at [[1956 Summer Olympics|Melbourne 1956]] and [[1960 Summer Olympics|Rome 1960]].\n\nTrotter returned to Britain in the early 1960s. In 1965, a head-on car collision caused injuries which impaired his mobility. Trotter returned to Guernsey in 1966, taking ownership of a local gun shop. He won H.M. The Queen's Prize in 1975, becoming only the second winner of the event from the island, and represented Guernsey in three consecutive Commonwealth Games from 1974, winning a bronze medal in the Fullbore Rifle individual event at [[1982 Commonwealth Games|Brisbane 1982]]. Trotter also represented [[Great Britain]] and [[Scotland]], before retiring from active shooting in 2001. He retained the presidency of the [[Elizabeth College (Guernsey)#Alumni|Old Elizabethan Rifle Club]] until his death in 2003\n\n{{TOClimit|4}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTrotter was born on 8 February 1923 in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was the son of James Maitland Yorke Trotter (2 March 1888 \u2013 {{circa}} 1960)<ref>{{cite web |title=TROTTER, James Maitland Yorke |url=http://to-lo.co.uk/familytree/ppl/1/e/c980a883b4f1d79bbe1.html |website=to-lo.co.uk |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> who generally went by his middle name, Maitland, and Margaret Dippie Trotter ({{nee|Duncan; died 30 October 1962}}).<ref name=\"family tree\">{{cite web |title=DUNCAN, Margaret Dippie |url=http://to-lo.co.uk/familytree/ppl/9/e/c980a885317331b62e9.html |website=to-lo.co.uk |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> Trotter's parents married in October 1921, two years before his birth.<ref name=\"family tree\"/> After his birth, Trotter's mother, a post-office clerk at the time, moved with him to [[Uganda]], where his father was working as a surveyor in the Department of Land and Surveys in the [[Colonial Service]]. In the six years after his birth, Trotter accompanied his parents on a near-permanent [[safari]] owing to the itinerant nature of his father's work. He and his family mixed almost exclusively within the British colonial community where they enjoyed a busy social life, captured by his mother, who was a keen photographer.<ref name=\"bristol bio\">{{cite web |title=2001/090 |url=http://museums.bristol.gov.uk/details.php?irn=238168 |website=museums.bristol.gov.uk |publisher=Bristol Museum Archives |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of six, Trotter returned to [[England]] where he attended [[boarding school]],<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> while his parents lived in [[Nigeria]] and later undertook a tour of the [[Caribbean]] through his father's work as a surveyor in the [[British Empire]].<ref name=\"archives\"/> In 1936, Trotter and his family relocated more permanently to Guernsey.<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web |title=2001/090/2 |url=http://museums.bristol.gov.uk/details.php?irn=330038 |website=museums.bristol.gov.uk |publisher=Bristol Museums Galleries Archives |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> He was educated in Guernsey at [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey|Elizabeth College]], an all-boys public school, where he started shooting, and represented the school at the schools' championships at [[Bisley, Surrey|Bisley]] three times, captaining the team in 1940. That year, Trotter was evacuated along with fellow students and staff to [[Great Hucklow]], [[Derbyshire]] during the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]]. He took with him part of his father's valuable stamp collection, addresses of friends in England and twelve pounds, which was all the money that was in the house at that time.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n==Life and career==\n===Photography career; Olympic games: 1940\u20131966===\nAfter leaving school, Trotter joined the [[Royal Engineers]] with whom he served during the [[Second World War]]. Once the war was over, Trotter, then a Captain, commanded a group of German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]] in [[Suez Canal|the Canal Zone in Egypt]] charged with constructing and maintaining the water supply and filtration plants. In 1949, he undertook a photography course at the [[London College of Communication|London School of Photo Engraving and Lithography]], obtaining a first-class pass in his exams. Trotter then established a photographic business in [[Nairobi]], Kenya from 1951 to 1962. He achieved considerable success as a photographer, and his work spanned a broad range of material, including weddings, natural history and news items. He also undertook commercial commissions showing industries of the time, and public occasions such as sporting and cultural events and royal visits. Trotter also produced films, including a nature film about baboons which won a [[Blue Ribbon Awards|Blue Ribbon Award]] for photography. During this time, Trotter represented Kenya in the Men's Smallbore Rifle events (Prone and Three Positions) at two [[Olympic Games]]\u2013[[1956 Summer Olympics|Melbourne 1956]] and [[1960 Summer Olympics|Rome 1960]]\u2013and the World Championships in 1962.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nHe returned to London in the early 1960s, before moving to [[Fleet, Hampshire]] where he joined the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]] at [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]] and later [[Aberporth]], Wales as a photographer. One of his many tasks with the establishment was photographing the [[de Havilland Comet]].<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> On 15 February 1963, Trotter married his wife, Joan Peary.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/><ref name=\"byers\">{{cite web |title=TROTTER OF BYERS GREEN HALL |url=http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~trotter/genealogy/trotter_of_byers_green_hall.htm |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> The two were involved in a head-on car collision in 1965, which rendered both disabled. In spite of the injuries which impaired his mobility, he was still able to continue shooting.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n\n===Queen's success; Commonwealth games: 1966\u20131987===\n{{quote box|quote=\"I like tie-shoots, they bring out the best in me.\"|source=\u2014Trotter's phlegmatic response to being told he'd tied with five others for the Queen's Prize.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>|width=26%|align=right}}\n\nIn 1966, Trotter returned to Guernsey where he took over a long-established gun shop.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was named Scottish Champion in 1972. In 1975, Trotter won H.M. The Queen's Prize after winning a six-way tie-shoot; it was the first time in history the competition had been decided in a six-way tie.<ref name=\"parker martel\">{{cite book |last1=Bruce Parker |first1=Mike Martel |title=History of Guernsey Rifle Shooting |date=1 October 2016 |publisher=Blurb, Incorporated |location=Guernsey |isbn=9781367173392 |edition=2nd }}</ref> In doing so, Trotter became only the second Guernseyman to win the competition, and he remains the island's most recent winner.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was awarded a gold medal, a gold badge, and \u00a3250 donated personally by the monarch herself, [[Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"top marks\">{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Bruce |title=Top marks |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2005/07/19/top-marks/ |accessdate=3 July 2019 |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=19 July 2005}}</ref> The ''[[Guernsey Press|Guernsey Evening Press]]'' reported on Trotter's arrival home in Guernsey as follows:\n\n<blockquote>His greatest ambition achieved, Queen's Prize winner Charles Trotter returned home to a hero's welcome last night. With the special blue background badge on his blazer and the coveted gold medal in his pocket, he stood on the after-deck of the mailboat waving his white hat to the big crowd who had gathered to welcome him back. The first to greet him when he came ashore were his father and his wife, Joan. Theirs were only the first of a torrent of congratulations to be showered upon him. The occasion belonged not only to Charles Trotter but also the Guernsey Rifle Club. Members had turned out in force. Among them was Captain Don Bisset, who remembers the only other Guernsey winner of the Queen's Prize, Private William Priaulx, whose success was in 1899. A garland of red and orange flowers was placed around the new winner's neck before he was chaired in traditional Bisley style round the New Jetty in a procession led by the Salvation Army Band ... Visitors and locals who lined the Upper Walk applauded loudly as the chair carried by members of the Guernsey Rifle Club made its way slowly along the jetty. The man who was attracting all the attention seemed to take everything as calmly as he had done the tie-shoot on Saturday.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/></blockquote>\n\nSoon after his celebrated return to Guernsey, Trotter was voted as the island's Sportsman of the Year and was asked by the Guernsey Postal Services to be featured on one of its stamps in a series depicting disability in sport. Trotter reached the Queen's Final a further seven times, the St Georges top twenty-five twice and won five bronze crosses in the Grand Aggregate. He fired twenty times for Guernsey in the Kolapore, and represented Scotland, the Channel Islands and Guernsey in the Mackinnon. Trotter represented the island in three consecutive [[Commonwealth Games]] from 1974, winning a bronze medal in the Fullbore Rifle event in the 1982 edition held in [[Brisbane]], Australia.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> Trotter achieved tremendous success in local competitions also, winning the island smallbore championship twelve times from 1971 to 1986. Representing [[Great Britain]], Trotter competed in the Smallbore World Championships in 1974 and 1982, and also represented Great Britain in 300 metres shooting, competing a number of times in the Masters and Nordic Championships. Trotter represented his birth-country, Scotland, fifteen times between 1958 and 1987.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n===Later years: 1987\u20132003===\nTrotter was named Hampshire Fullbore Champion in 1994, and in 2000 he captained the Scotland national team.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> Throughout his career, Trotter reportedly made his own foresight rings; as he got older they got thinner until eventually he made them out of fuse wire.<ref>{{cite book |title=Target Shooter Magazine |date=December 2012 |page=115 |url=https://www.longrangeitalia.com/wp-content/uploads/dec_12_dps.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> In 2001, Trotter gave up active participation in shooting, but continued to hold the Presidency of the [[Elizabeth College (Guernsey)#Alumni|Old Elizabethan Rifle Club]] until his death, aged 80, in 2003.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\nTrotter's achievements in both smallbore and fullbore rifle shooting make him one Guernsey's most decorated marksmen, and he remains the last Guernseyman to win the Queen's Prize.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Batiste |first1=Rob |title=Maces fly the gale-strewn flag |url=https://guernseypress.com/sport/2018/07/30/maces-fly-the-gale-strewn-flag/ |accessdate=3 July 2019 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press}}</ref> Trotter's substantial collection of shooting silver and memorabilia is held in an exhibit in [[Castle Cornet]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=Winter 2003 |date=Winter 2003 |volume=LXXXII  |issue=3 |page=82 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2003winter.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> In 2005, Trotter was one of the first ten people to be inducted into the Guernsey Sports Commission's wall of fame.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guernsey's greatest revealed |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2005/02/02/guernseys-greatest-revealed/ |accessdate=4 July 2019 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=2 February 2005}}</ref> After his death, Trotter's ashes were scattered at Bisley at the beginning of the 2004 Imperial Meeting.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nHe was generally regarded as a calm and mild-mannered character, with his obituary describing him as \"a quiet man with a wealth of experience\"; \"... always eager to hear how other members of the team had performed, but would say little of his achievements\".<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nRegarded as a leading commercial photographer in Kenya in the 1950s, Trotter's photography during that time, particularly of British-Kenyan [[Upper class|high society]], along with his collection of around 50,000 negatives is regarded as a rich resource for the study of Kenya immediately prior to [[History of Kenya#Independence|its independence in 1962]].<ref name=\"bristol bio\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Teller Magazine: The Art of Storytelling |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/photography/8087437/Teller-Magazine-The-Art-of-Storytelling.html?image=4 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===International competitions===\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 90%;}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing  {{flagIOC|KEN|1956 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1956\n|rowspan=2|[[Shooting at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Melbourne]], Australia\n|42nd\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Three Positions, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1,030 ex 1200]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1956 Melbourne Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Three Positions, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1956/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-three-positions-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|41st\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1956 Summer Olympics|586 ex 600]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1956 Melbourne Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1956/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-prone-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1960\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Rome]], Italy\n|37th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1960 Summer Olympics|574 ex 600]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1960 Roma Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1960/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-prone-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing {{GGY}}\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1974\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n|6th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1974 British Commonwealth Games#Shooting|587 ex 600]]<ref name=\"cwg results\">{{cite web |title=Athletes & Results: Charles Trotter |url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/50554 |website=thecgf.com |publisher=The Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1978\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Edmonton]], Canada\n|16th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1978 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1177 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1982\n|rowspan=4|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=4|[[Brisbane]], Australia\n|5th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1174 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|11th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres (Pairs)}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1163 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#c96;\"|3rd\n|{{small|Fullbore Rifle, Queen's Prize individual}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|384 ex 405]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|7th\n|{{small|Fullbore Rifle, Queen's Prize pairs}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|557 ex 600]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n===National titles===\n*Fullbore rifle\n**H.M. The Queen's Prize: 1975<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n**Hampshire Fullbore Championship: 1994<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Guernsey Fullbore Championship: 1979<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n**Guernsey Fullbore Grand Aggregate: 1973<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n*Smallbore rifle\n**Scottish Smallbore Championship: 1972<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Guernsey Smallbore Championship: 12 times<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Smallbore Indoor Veteran Championship: 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trotter, Charles}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to Kenya]]\n[[Category:Kenyan male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:British male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Guernsey sportsmen]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1974 British Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1978 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1982 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in shooting]]\n[[Category:People educated at Elizabeth College, Guernsey]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British sports shooter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Charles Trotter\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = Charles Maitland Yorke Trotter\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1923|2|8}}\n| birth_place    = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2003|9|8|1923|2|8}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=Winter 2003 |date=Winter 2003 |volume=LXXXII  |issue=3 |page=82 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2003winter.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n| death_place    = [[Surrey]], England\n| occupation         = {{hlist|{{nowrap|Sports shooter}}|photographer}}\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Joan Peary|1963}}\n| partner            = \n| parents            = {{plainlist|\n* James 'Maitland' Trotter (father)\n* Margaret Trotter (mother)\n}}\n| module        =\n{{Infobox military person \n| embed         = yes\n| allegiance    = United Kingdom\n|branch_label       = Branch\n| branch        = [[British Army]]\n|serviceyears_label = Service&nbsp;years\n|serviceyears   = 1940\u20131965\n| rank          = [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]]\n| unit          = [[Royal Engineers]]\n| battles_label      = Conflict\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n}}\n| module2           = \n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| embed           = yes\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| country        = [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] {{small|(1951&ndash;1962)}}<br>Scotland {{small|(1958&ndash;2000)}}<br>[[Guernsey]] {{small|(1966&ndash;2001)}}\n| sport          = [[Sport shooter|Rifle shooting]]\n| club           = Guernsey Rifle Club\n| show-medals    = no\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Sport | [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{GGY}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Commonwealth Games}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1982 Commonwealth Games|1982 Brisbane]]|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Rifle|Fullbore singles]]}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Charles Maitland Yorke Trotter''' (8 February 1923 &ndash; 8 September 2003)<ref name=\"NRA obituary\">{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=National Rifle Association Journal |date=Spring 2004 |volume=LXXXIII |issue=1 |page=54 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2004spring.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> was a British [[Shooting sport|sports shooter]] who represented [[Guernsey]] and [[Kenya Colony|Kenya]] in both fullbore and smallbore disciplines, and also sustained a successful career as a commercial photographer. Trotter's achievements in target rifle shooting make him one Guernsey's most decorated sportsmen. Best remembered for his prowess in fullbore rifle shooting, Trotter won [[National Rifle Association of the United Kingdom|H.M. The Queen's Prize]] in 1975, and is a [[Commonwealth Games]] medallist, winning a bronze medal in [[1982 Commonwealth Games|1982]] while representing Guernsey. Also a champion smallbore shooter, Trotter represented Kenya in two [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic Games]].\n\nBorn in [[Edinburgh]], Trotter was educated at [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey]], where he captained the school shooting team. He later served during [[World War II]] with the [[Royal Engineers]] before commanding a group of German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]] in [[Egypt]] after the war. After studying photography, Trotter established a photographic business in [[Nairobi]] from 1951 to 1962. He achieved considerable success as a commercial photographer, and his work is now regarded as a rich resource for the study of Kenya immediately prior to [[History of Kenya#Independence|its independence in 1962]]. During this time, Trotter represented Kenya at [[1956 Summer Olympics|Melbourne 1956]] and [[1960 Summer Olympics|Rome 1960]].\n\nTrotter returned to Britain in the early 1960s. In 1965, a head-on car collision caused injuries which impaired his mobility. Trotter returned to Guernsey in 1966, taking ownership of a local gun shop. He won H.M. The Queen's Prize in 1975, becoming only the second winner of the event from the island, and represented Guernsey in three consecutive Commonwealth Games from 1974, winning a bronze medal in the Fullbore Rifle individual event at [[1982 Commonwealth Games|Brisbane 1982]]. Trotter also represented [[Great Britain]] and [[Scotland]], before retiring from active shooting in 2001. He retained the presidency of the [[Elizabeth College (Guernsey)#Alumni|Old Elizabethan Rifle Club]] until his death in 2003\n\n{{TOClimit|4}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTrotter was born on 8 February 1923 in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was the son of James Maitland Yorke Trotter (2 March 1888 \u2013 {{circa}} 1960)<ref>{{cite web |title=TROTTER, James Maitland Yorke |url=http://to-lo.co.uk/familytree/ppl/1/e/c980a883b4f1d79bbe1.html |website=to-lo.co.uk |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> who generally went by his middle name, Maitland, and Margaret Dippie Trotter ({{nee|Duncan; died 30 October 1962}}).<ref name=\"family tree\">{{cite web |title=DUNCAN, Margaret Dippie |url=http://to-lo.co.uk/familytree/ppl/9/e/c980a885317331b62e9.html |website=to-lo.co.uk |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> Trotter's parents married in October 1921, two years before his birth.<ref name=\"family tree\"/> After his birth, Trotter's mother, a post-office clerk at the time, moved with him to [[Uganda]], where his father was working as a surveyor in the Department of Land and Surveys in the [[Colonial Service]]. In the six years after his birth, Trotter accompanied his parents on a near-permanent [[safari]] owing to the itinerant nature of his father's work. He and his family mixed almost exclusively within the British colonial community where they enjoyed a busy social life, captured by his mother, who was a keen photographer.<ref name=\"bristol bio\">{{cite web |title=2001/090 |url=http://museums.bristol.gov.uk/details.php?irn=238168 |website=museums.bristol.gov.uk |publisher=Bristol Museum Archives |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of six, Trotter returned to [[England]] where he attended [[boarding school]],<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> while his parents lived in [[Nigeria]] and later undertook a tour of the [[Caribbean]] through his father's work as a surveyor in the [[British Empire]].<ref name=\"archives\"/> In 1936, Trotter and his family relocated more permanently to Guernsey.<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web |title=2001/090/2 |url=http://museums.bristol.gov.uk/details.php?irn=330038 |website=museums.bristol.gov.uk |publisher=Bristol Museums Galleries Archives |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> He was educated in Guernsey at [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey|Elizabeth College]], an all-boys public school, where he started shooting, and represented the school at the schools' championships at [[Bisley, Surrey|Bisley]] three times, captaining the team in 1940. That year, Trotter was evacuated along with fellow students and staff to [[Great Hucklow]], [[Derbyshire]] during the [[German occupation of the Channel Islands]]. He took with him part of his father's valuable stamp collection, addresses of friends in England and twelve pounds, which was all the money that was in the house at that time.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n==Life and career==\n===Photography career; Olympic games: 1940\u20131966===\nAfter leaving school, Trotter joined the [[Royal Engineers]] with whom he served during the [[Second World War]]. Once the war was over, Trotter, then a Captain, commanded a group of German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]] in [[Suez Canal|the Canal Zone in Egypt]] charged with constructing and maintaining the water supply and filtration plants. In 1949, he undertook a photography course at the [[London College of Communication|London School of Photo Engraving and Lithography]], obtaining a first-class pass in his exams. Trotter then established a photographic business in [[Nairobi]], Kenya from 1951 to 1962. He achieved considerable success as a photographer, and his work spanned a broad range of material, including weddings, natural history and news items. He also undertook commercial commissions showing industries of the time, and public occasions such as sporting and cultural events and royal visits. Trotter also produced films, including a nature film about baboons which won a [[Blue Ribbon Awards|Blue Ribbon Award]] for photography. During this time, Trotter represented Kenya in the Men's Smallbore Rifle events (Prone and Three Positions) at two [[Olympic Games]]\u2013[[1956 Summer Olympics|Melbourne 1956]] and [[1960 Summer Olympics|Rome 1960]]\u2013and the World Championships in 1962.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nHe returned to London in the early 1960s, before moving to [[Fleet, Hampshire]] where he joined the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]] at [[Farnborough, Hampshire|Farnborough]] and later [[Aberporth]], Wales as a photographer. One of his many tasks with the establishment was photographing the [[de Havilland Comet]].<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> On 15 February 1963, Trotter married his wife, Joan Peary.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/><ref name=\"byers\">{{cite web |title=TROTTER OF BYERS GREEN HALL |url=http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~trotter/genealogy/trotter_of_byers_green_hall.htm |accessdate=3 July 2019}}</ref> The two were involved in a head-on car collision in 1965, which rendered both disabled. In spite of the injuries which impaired his mobility, he was still able to continue shooting.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n\n===Queen's success; Commonwealth games: 1966\u20131987===\n{{quote box|quote=\"I like tie-shoots, they bring out the best in me.\"|source=\u2014Trotter's phlegmatic response to being told he'd tied with five others for the Queen's Prize.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>|width=26%|align=right}}\n\nIn 1966, Trotter returned to Guernsey where he took over a long-established gun shop.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was named Scottish Champion in 1972. In 1975, Trotter won H.M. The Queen's Prize after winning a six-way tie-shoot; it was the first time in history the competition had been decided in a six-way tie.<ref name=\"parker martel\">{{cite book |last1=Bruce Parker |first1=Mike Martel |title=History of Guernsey Rifle Shooting |date=1 October 2016 |publisher=Blurb, Incorporated |location=Guernsey |isbn=9781367173392 |edition=2nd }}</ref> In doing so, Trotter became only the second Guernseyman to win the competition, and he remains the island's most recent winner.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> He was awarded a gold medal, a gold badge, and \u00a3250 donated personally by the monarch herself, [[Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"top marks\">{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Bruce |title=Top marks |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2005/07/19/top-marks/ |accessdate=3 July 2019 |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=19 July 2005}}</ref> The Guernsey Evening Press reported on Trotter's arrival home in Guernsey as follows:\n\n<blockquote>His greatest ambition achieved, Queen's Prize winner Charles Trotter returned home to a hero's welcome last night. With the special blue background badge on his blazer and the coveted gold medal in his pocket, he stood on the after-deck of the mailboat waving his white hat to the big crowd who had gathered to welcome him back. The first to greet him when he came ashore were his father and his wife, Joan. Theirs were only the first of a torrent of congratulations to be showered upon him. The occasion belonged not only to Charles Trotter but also the Guernsey Rifle Club. Members had turned out in force. Among them was Captain Don Bisset, who remembers the only other Guernsey winner of the Queen's Prize, Private William Priaulx, whose success was in 1899. A garland of red and orange flowers was placed around the new winner's neck before he was chaired in traditional Bisley style round the New Jetty in a procession led by the Salvation Army Band ... Visitors and locals who lined the Upper Walk applauded loudly as the chair carried by members of the Guernsey Rifle Club made its way slowly along the jetty. The man who was attracting all the attention seemed to take everything as calmly as he had done the tie-shoot on Saturday.<ref name=\"parker martel\"/></blockquote>\n\nSoon after his celebrated return to Guernsey, Trotter was voted as the island's Sportsman of the Year and was asked by the Guernsey Postal Services to be featured on one of its stamps in a series depicting disability in sport. Trotter reached the Queen's Final a further seven times, the St Georges top twenty-five twice and won five bronze crosses in the Grand Aggregate. He fired twenty times for Guernsey in the Kolapore, and represented Scotland, the Channel Islands and Guernsey in the Mackinnon. Trotter represented the island in three consecutive [[Commonwealth Games]] from 1974, winning a bronze medal in the Fullbore Rifle event in the 1982 edition held in [[Brisbane]], Australia.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> Trotter achieved tremendous success in local competitions also, winning the island smallbore championship twelve times from 1971 to 1986. Representing [[Great Britain]], Trotter competed in the Smallbore World Championships in 1974 and 1982, and also represented Great Britain in 300 metres shooting, competing a number of times in the Masters and Nordic Championships. Trotter represented his birth-country, Scotland, fifteen times between 1958 and 1987.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n===Later years: 1987\u20132003===\nTrotter was named Hampshire Fullbore Champion in 1994, and in 2000 he captained the Scotland national team.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/> Throughout his career, Trotter reportedly made his own foresight rings; as he got older they got thinner until eventually he made them out of fuse wire.<ref>{{cite book |title=Target Shooter Magazine |date=December 2012 |page=115 |url=https://www.longrangeitalia.com/wp-content/uploads/dec_12_dps.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> In 2001, Trotter gave up active participation in shooting, but continued to hold the Presidency of the [[Elizabeth College (Guernsey)#Alumni|Old Elizabethan Rifle Club]] until his death, aged 80, in 2003.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n== Legacy ==\nTrotter's achievements in both smallbore and fullbore rifle shooting make him one Guernsey's most decorated marksmen, and he remains the last Guernseyman to win the Queen's Prize.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Batiste |first1=Rob |title=Maces fly the gale-strewn flag |url=https://guernseypress.com/sport/2018/07/30/maces-fly-the-gale-strewn-flag/ |accessdate=3 July 2019 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press}}</ref> Trotter's substantial collection of shooting silver and memorabilia is held in an exhibit in [[Castle Cornet]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=National Rifle Association Journal |journal=Winter 2003 |date=Winter 2003 |volume=LXXXII  |issue=3 |page=82 |url=https://nra.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/2003winter.pdf |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> In 2005, Trotter was one of the first ten people to be inducted into the Guernsey Sports Commission's wall of fame.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guernsey's greatest revealed |url=https://guernseypress.com/news/2005/02/02/guernseys-greatest-revealed/ |accessdate=4 July 2019 |work=guernseypress.com |publisher=Guernsey Press |date=2 February 2005}}</ref> After his death, Trotter's ashes were scattered at Bisley at the beginning of the 2004 Imperial Meeting.<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nHe was generally regarded as a calm and mild-mannered character, with his obituary describing him as \"a quiet man with a wealth of experience\"; \"... always eager to hear how other members of the team had performed, but would say little of his achievements\".<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\nRegarded as a leading commercial photographer in Kenya in the 1950s, Trotter's photography during that time, particularly of British-Kenyan [[Upper class|high society]], along with his collection of around 50,000 negatives is regarded as a rich resource for the study of Kenya immediately prior to [[History of Kenya#Independence|its independence in 1962]].<ref name=\"bristol bio\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Teller Magazine: The Art of Storytelling |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/photography/8087437/Teller-Magazine-The-Art-of-Storytelling.html?image=4 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n===International competitions===\n{| {{AchievementTable|Event=yes|class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 90%;}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing  {{flagIOC|KEN|1956 Summer}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1956\n|rowspan=2|[[Shooting at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Melbourne]], Australia\n|42nd\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Three Positions, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1,030 ex 1200]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1956 Melbourne Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Three Positions, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1956/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-three-positions-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|41st\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1956 Summer Olympics|586 ex 600]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1956 Melbourne Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1956/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-prone-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1960\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Rome]], Italy\n|37th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[Shooting at the 1960 Summer Olympics|574 ex 600]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Shooting at the 1960 Roma Summer Games: Men's Small-Bore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1960/SHO/mens-small-bore-rifle-prone-50-metres.html |website=sports-reference.com |publisher=SR Olympic Sports |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Representing {{GGY}}\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1974\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n|6th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1974 British Commonwealth Games#Shooting|587 ex 600]]<ref name=\"cwg results\">{{cite web |title=Athletes & Results: Charles Trotter |url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/50554 |website=thecgf.com |publisher=The Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=1|1978\n|rowspan=1|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Edmonton]], Canada\n|16th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1978 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1177 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1982\n|rowspan=4|[[Shooting at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]\n|rowspan=4|[[Brisbane]], Australia\n|5th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1174 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|11th\n|{{small|Men's Smallbore Rifle, Prone, 50 metres (Pairs)}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|1163 ex 1200]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#c96;\"|3rd\n|{{small|Fullbore Rifle, Queen's Prize individual}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|384 ex 405]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|7th\n|{{small|Fullbore Rifle, Queen's Prize pairs}}\n|[[1982 Commonwealth Games#Shooting|557 ex 600]]<ref name=\"cwg results\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n===National titles===\n*Fullbore rifle\n**H.M. The Queen's Prize: 1975<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n**Hampshire Fullbore Championship: 1994<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Guernsey Fullbore Championship: 1979<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n**Guernsey Fullbore Grand Aggregate: 1973<ref name=\"parker martel\"/>\n*Smallbore rifle\n**Scottish Smallbore Championship: 1972<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Guernsey Smallbore Championship: 12 times<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n**Smallbore Indoor Veteran Championship: 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988<ref name=\"NRA obituary\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trotter, Charles}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish emigrants to Kenya]]\n[[Category:Kenyan male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:British male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Guernsey sportsmen]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1974 British Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1978 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category